# Architecture Rules

This is a Next.js 15 (App Router) + Supabase project. Every external service is **pluggable behind an interface**. See `ProjectSpec.md` for the full spec.

## Non-negotiables

- **`process.env` is read in exactly one file: `lib/config.ts`.** Never anywhere else. Other code reads from the exported `config` object.
- **Pages and API routes never call Supabase directly.** They call services in `lib/services/*`. Services call repos in `lib/repos/*`. Only repos talk to the DB.
- **Every external capability has an adapter.** Cache, storage, rate-limiting, errors, logging, search. Each lives in `lib/<capability>/` with: `index.ts` (interface), `<default>.ts` (free impl), `<upgrade>.ts` (paid impl), `factory.ts`.
- **Required env vars at boot: only Supabase + `REVALIDATE_SECRET`.** Everything else is optional and gated on env presence.

## Layering

```
app/* (pages, API routes)
  └─> lib/services/*   ← business logic, caching, validation
        └─> lib/repos/*   ← raw DB queries only
              └─> lib/db/client.ts
        └─> lib/<adapter>/factory.ts   ← cache, storage, etc.
```

Skipping a layer (e.g. calling a repo from a page) is a review-blocking issue.

## Validation

All external input — request bodies, query params, env — passes through a `zod` schema before use. Schemas live in `lib/db/schema.ts` (DB shapes) or alongside the route (request shapes).

## Don't

- Don't introduce a new external service without adding it as an adapter with a free fallback.
- Don't use `OFFSET` for pagination — cursor pagination only (see `lib/utils/cursor.ts`).
- Don't store mutable hot counters on the `images` row — use `like_counts` + cache.
